42
00:01:54,659 --> 00:01:56,789
But who was this person in the painting?

43
00:01:56,789 --> 00:02:01,319
People have always been curious about 
the identity of the woman in the painting.

44
00:02:01,319 --> 00:02:03,629
The first revelation about this was made by

45
00:02:03,629 --> 00:02:06,252
an Italian artist named Giorgio Vasari,

46
00:02:06,252 --> 00:02:10,660
who wrote the autobiography 
of Leonardo da Vinci in 1550.

47
00:02:10,660 --> 00:02:12,375
According to Vasari, this woman was

48
00:02:12,375 --> 00:02:14,103
Lisa Gherardini.

49
00:02:14,103 --> 00:02:17,949
She was married to a silk trader who lived in Florence,

50
00:02:17,949 --> 00:02:19,462
Francesco Giocondo.

51
00:02:19,462 --> 00:02:23,625
He believed that Francesco had 
commissioned this painting of his wife

52
00:02:23,625 --> 00:02:26,555
and that's the origin of the names of this painting.

53
00:02:26,555 --> 00:02:28,411
The first name that we all know,

54
00:02:28,411 --> 00:02:29,514
Mona Lisa,

55
00:02:29,514 --> 00:02:31,156
derived from Madonna Lisa.

56
00:02:31,156 --> 00:02:32,885
Traditionally, in Italian,

57
00:02:32,885 --> 00:02:36,055
the word Madonna was used to mean Madam.

58
00:02:36,055 --> 00:02:38,490
So, Madonna Lisa meant Madam Lisa.

59
00:02:38,490 --> 00:02:41,696
The word Madonna was later shortened to Monna.

60
00:02:41,696 --> 00:02:42,824
Monna with a double N.

61
00:02:42,824 --> 00:02:45,066
When this was written in English

62
00:02:45,066 --> 00:02:46,558
an N was dropped

63
00:02:46,558 --> 00:02:48,709
and Monna became Mona.

64
00:02:48,709 --> 00:02:50,756
So Mona Lisa means

65
00:02:50,756 --> 00:02:52,429
Madam Lisa or Lady Lisa.

66
00:02:52,429 --> 00:02:54,565
And then comes Mona Lisa's other name

67
00:02:54,565 --> 00:02:56,706
which is La Gioconda.

68
00:02:56,706 --> 00:02:58,671
After her marriage, Lisa Gherardini

69
00:02:58,671 --> 00:03:00,485
became Lisa Giocondo.

70
00:03:00,485 --> 00:03:03,897
Interestingly, in Italian, Giocondo means

71
00:03:03,897 --> 00:03:06,289
light-hearted or cheerful.

72
00:03:06,289 --> 00:03:07,826
Meaning, bright and joyful.

73
00:03:07,826 --> 00:03:11,203
And today, Mona Lisa is very famous for her smile.

74
00:03:11,203 --> 00:03:12,853
So that's where it got its name,

75
00:03:12,853 --> 00:03:13,917
La Giocondo.

76
00:03:13,917 --> 00:03:16,608
In French, the word Giocondo is written with a J,

77
00:03:16,608 --> 00:03:18,327
like this, Joconde.

78
00:03:18,327 --> 00:03:21,734
So that's why when you go to the Louvre Museum in Paris

79
00:03:21,734 --> 00:03:23,562
and see the painting of Mona Lisa,

80
00:03:23,562 --> 00:03:26,184
in French, it would be identified as La Joconde.

81
00:03:26,184 --> 00:03:27,649
Now, the interesting thing is that

82
00:03:27,649 --> 00:03:29,765
in 1550, despite this revelation,

83
00:03:29,765 --> 00:03:31,580
people were not ready to believe that

84
00:03:31,580 --> 00:03:33,966
Vasari's narrative was correct.

85
00:03:33,966 --> 00:03:35,568
Many theories started to emerge

86
00:03:35,568 --> 00:03:37,717
about this woman being someone else.

87
00:03:37,717 --> 00:03:40,064
Some people said that she 
was Leonardo da Vinci's mother.

88
00:03:40,064 --> 00:03:44,659
Some said that this was a painting 
of a queen from the Italian aristocracy.

89
00:03:44,659 --> 00:03:46,394
The most interesting theory was that

90
00:03:46,394 --> 00:03:49,199
in this painting, da Vinci painted himself.

91
00:03:49,199 --> 00:03:50,735
That this painting is not of a woman.

92
00:03:50,735 --> 00:03:53,578
but in fact a self-portrait of Da Vinci.

93
00:03:53,578 --> 00:03:55,685
Where he imagined

94
00:03:55,685 --> 00:03:58,171
how he would have looked had he been a woman.

95
00:03:58,171 --> 00:04:03,347
This theory was promoted by 
artist Lilian Schwartz in an article in 1987.

96
00:04:03,347 --> 00:04:05,285
She used digital tools to

97
00:04:05,285 --> 00:04:07,491
try to show similarities between

98
00:04:07,491 --> 00:04:09,571
Leonardo Da Vinci's face

99
00:04:09,571 --> 00:04:11,233
and Mona Lisa's image.

100
00:04:11,233 --> 00:04:13,364
With this logic, any two faces

101
00:04:13,364 --> 00:04:16,430
can be seen as similar by placing them on top of each other.

102
00:04:16,430 --> 00:04:18,801
But today, we can say with a lot of certainty that

103
00:04:18,801 --> 00:04:20,565
the woman painted here

104
00:04:20,565 --> 00:04:22,315
is indeed Lisa Giocondo.

105
00:04:22,315 --> 00:04:24,082
A professor living in Florence

106
00:04:24,082 --> 00:04:26,435
researched this for 25 years

107
00:04:26,435 --> 00:04:29,095
and found the archives

108
00:04:29,095 --> 00:04:32,067
and in 2004, he discovered clear evidence

109
00:04:32,067 --> 00:04:33,879
to prove this fact.

110
00:04:33,879 --> 00:04:35,111
He also found that

111
00:04:35,111 --> 00:04:37,938
the da Vinci family had a close relationship

112
00:04:37,938 --> 00:04:39,945
with Francesco Giocondo's family.

113
00:04:39,945 --> 00:04:42,012
He also found a record that

114
00:04:42,012 --> 00:04:45,915
Lisa's marriage was registered on 5th March 1495

115
00:04:45,915 --> 00:04:47,784
when Lisa was 16 years old

116
00:04:47,784 --> 00:04:50,377
and Francesco was around 30 years old.

117
00:04:50,377 --> 00:04:53,054
He found that Leonardo da Vinci's father

118
00:04:53,054 --> 00:04:55,810
and Lisa's husband knew each other very well.

119
