00:10:55,283 --> 00:10:56,893
To perfect this smile,

262
00:10:56,893 --> 00:10:59,049
da Vinci spent the most time.

263
00:10:59,049 --> 00:11:01,889
He spent many nights in a hospital in Florence,

264
00:11:01,889 --> 00:11:05,297
where he used to go and remove the skin of d3ad bodies.

265
00:11:05,297 --> 00:11:08,964
He wanted to study the facial muscles and nerves

266
00:11:08,964 --> 00:11:11,559
and how they work together to create a smile.

267
00:11:11,559 --> 00:11:13,288
He wrote in his book that

268
00:11:13,288 --> 00:11:14,831
"the muscles which move the lips

269
00:11:14,831 --> 00:11:16,472
are more numerous in man

270
00:11:16,472 --> 00:11:17,944
than in any other animal."

271
00:11:17,944 --> 00:11:21,272
It was very difficult for him to dissect the muscles of the lips

272
00:11:21,272 --> 00:11:25,570
because the muscles here are tiny and numerous.

273
00:11:25,570 --> 00:11:27,251
During this experiment,

274
00:11:27,251 --> 00:11:29,352
da Vinci studied horses as well.

275
00:11:29,352 --> 00:11:32,762
He compared human expressions to that of horses.

276
00:11:32,762 --> 00:11:34,190
In the notes, he wrote,

277
00:11:34,190 --> 00:11:35,505
"Notice whether the muscle that

278
00:11:35,505 --> 00:11:37,078
raises the nostrils of the horse

279
00:11:37,078 --> 00:11:38,235
is the same as that which

280
00:11:38,235 --> 00:11:39,306
lies here in man."

281
00:11:39,306 --> 00:11:41,755
Hardly, throughout history, any other artist

282
00:11:41,755 --> 00:11:44,657
has dissected the faces of a horse and a human

283
00:11:44,657 --> 00:11:46,357
and done these experiments.

284
00:11:46,357 --> 00:11:49,058
His obsession with Mona Lisa's smile

285
00:11:49,058 --> 00:11:50,079
didn't end here.

286
00:11:50,079 --> 00:11:52,557
After this, he did research on optics as well.

287
00:11:52,557 --> 00:11:54,577
He found that the light rays

288
00:11:54,577 --> 00:11:57,110
don't merge together into a single point on our eyes,

289
00:11:57,110 --> 00:11:59,220
rather they spread out over the entire retina.

290
00:11:59,220 --> 00:12:01,033
The centre of the retina,

291
00:12:01,033 --> 00:12:02,461
known as the Fovea,

292
00:12:02,461 --> 00:12:05,292
helps us see the finest details.

293
00:12:05,292 --> 00:12:07,605
On the other hand, the rest of the retina

294
00:12:07,605 --> 00:12:10,550
picks up shadows and black-and-white imagery more.

295
00:12:10,550 --> 00:12:12,165
Using this knowledge,

296
00:12:12,165 --> 00:12:14,320
he focused on the shadows in such a way that

297
00:12:14,320 --> 00:12:17,583
even when you see the Mona Lisa in your peripheral vision,

298
00:12:17,583 --> 00:12:20,285
as in, if you are looking this way 
and Mona Lisa is on the other side,

299
00:12:20,285 --> 00:12:22,216
even if you are not paying attention to Mona Lisa,

300
00:12:22,216 --> 00:12:25,409
the effect of her smile is still there.

301
00:12:25,409 --> 00:12:27,253
When you look at her smile closely,

302
00:12:27,253 --> 00:12:29,858
you will see that its central line is a flat line,

303
00:12:29,858 --> 00:12:32,011
is why when you look at her smile,

304
00:12:32,011 --> 00:12:34,274
it looks like she is not smiling at all.

305
00:12:34,274 --> 00:12:37,731
But on the other hand, 
the shadows created using the Sfumato technique,

306
00:12:37,731 --> 00:12:40,114
have such an effect that

307
00:12:40,114 --> 00:12:41,993
when you look elsewhere,

308
00:12:41,993 --> 00:12:44,381
your peripheral vision sees that smile

309
00:12:44,381 --> 00:12:46,034
and its shadows are reflected.

310
00:12:46,034 --> 00:12:48,385
And then you feel that Lisa is smiling.

311
00:12:48,385 --> 00:12:50,698
How would it feel if I told you that

312
00:12:50,698 --> 00:12:52,841
the Mona Lisa is not one painting,

313
00:12:52,841 --> 00:12:54,310
rather two paintings.

314
00:12:54,310 --> 00:12:55,679
This is not a conspiracy theory,

315
00:12:55,679 --> 00:12:57,192
it's the truth.

316
00:12:57,192 --> 00:12:59,380
Mona Lisa's painting, as we know,

317
00:12:59,380 --> 00:13:02,328
a similar painting was created

318
00:13:02,328 --> 00:13:03,512
at the same time.

319
00:13:03,512 --> 00:13:05,617
The story of this second Mona Lisa began

320
00:13:05,617 --> 00:13:07,203
in the year 1504

321
00:13:07,203 --> 00:13:09,791
when another legendary artist named Raphael

322
00:13:09,791 --> 00:13:12,601
made a rough sketch using pen and ink.

323
00:13:12,601 --> 00:13:14,872
This sketch looked something like this

324
00:13:14,872 --> 00:13:16,896
and if you compare it with the Mona Lisa in Louvre,

325
00:13:16,896 --> 00:13:18,605
you can see a huge difference.

326
00:13:18,605 --> 00:13:20,169
In this sketch by Raphael,

327
00:13:20,169 --> 00:13:23,289
you can see two columns behind Mona Lisa.

328
00:13:23,289 --> 00:13:24,864
Here, the researchers believed that

329
00:13:24,864 --> 00:13:28,027
Raphael must have made his drawing based on the Mona Lisa painting.

330
00:13:28,027 --> 00:13:29,243
So, it was initially brushed off.

331
00:13:29,243 --> 00:13:33,605
But this theory was disproved by 
a German art historian in 1993.

332
00:13:33,605 --> 00:13:36,086
And Professor Pallanti, whom I had mentioned earlier,

333
00:13:36,086 --> 00:13:39,668
who had been researching the identity of the Mona Lisa for 25 years,

334
00:13:39,668 --> 00:13:42,676
confirmed that Raphael actually

335
00:13:42,676 --> 00:13:47,567
lived right in front of the Giocondo family in Florence.

336
00:13:47,567 --> 00:13:49,811
So, does this mean that Raphael

337
00:13:49,811 --> 00:13:51,075
made an original painting 

338
00:13:51,075 --> 00:13:52,334
on the same subject,

339
00:13:52,334 --> 00:13:54,603
with the same woman in the same pose?

340
00:13:54,603 --> 00:13:56,203
This seems quite unbelievable.

341
00:13:56,203 --> 00:13:58,264
Another answer to this question could be that

342
00:13:58,264 --> 00:14:00,894
another Mona Lisa painting exists

343
00:14:00,894 --> 00:14:03,951
which inspired Raphael to make this drawing.

344
00:14:03,951 --> 00:14:07,241
And this second Mona Lisa painting was revealed to the world

345
00:14:07,241 --> 00:14:08,867
in 1914.

346
00:14:08,867 --> 00:14:10,910
A novelist living near London,

347
00:14:10,910 --> 00:14:12,778
John R. Eyer,

348
00:14:12,778 --> 00:14:15,694
had a new version of the Mona Lisa.

349
00:14:15,694 --> 00:14:17,959
This is the new Mona Lisa painting.

350
00:14:17,959 --> 00:14:20,127
The same painting based on which

351
00:14:20,127 --> 00:14:21,307
Raphael made his drawing.

352
00:14:21,307 --> 00:14:22,801
This second Mona Lisa

353
00:14:22,801 --> 00:14:24,938
is 3.5 inches longer

354
00:14:24,938 --> 00:14:26,864
and 5 inches wider than the one in the Louvre.

355
00:14:26,864 --> 00:14:29,043
If you compare these two paintings,

356
00:14:29,043 --> 00:14:30,663
you will notice three things.

357
00:14:30,663 --> 00:14:33,549
First, the woman in this new Mona Lisa

358
00:14:33,549 --> 00:14:35,191
looks much younger.

359
00:14:35,191 --> 00:14:37,266
Second, the head in this new painting

360
00:14:37,266 --> 00:14:39,154
is tilted a little forward.

361
00:14:39,154 --> 00:14:41,623
And third, the expressions of this new Mona Lisa

362
00:14:41,623 --> 00:14:44,211
are very straightforward and clear.

363
00:14:44,211 --> 00:14:46,352
There is nothing mysterious about her smile

364
00:14:46,352 --> 00:14:48,053
that is in the Mona Lisa in Louvre.

365
00:14:48,053 --> 00:14:50,044
The two columns in the background

366
00:14:50,044 --> 00:14:52,607
are the ones seen in Raphael's drawing.

367
00:14:52,607 --> 00:14:54,175
Due to these reasons,

368
00:14:54,175 --> 00:14:56,468
a new theory is coined by the experts.

369
00:14:56,468 --> 00:15:01,009
That Leonardo da Vinci was actually working on two Mona Lisas.

370
00:15:01,009 --> 00:15:05,091
Leonardo da Vinci painted both these Mona Lisa.

371
00:15:05,091 --> 00:15:08,001
But the Isleworth Mona Lisa that was later discovered

372
00:15:08,001 --> 00:15:10,680
was the first version of da Vinci's painting.

373
00:15:10,680 --> 00:15:13,049
He was experimenting with his style then.

374
00:15:13,049 --> 00:15:16,439
And this is why the Mona Lisa in that painting

375
00:15:16,439 --> 00:15:20,587
looks younger than the other Mona Lisa.

376
00:15:20,587 --> 00:15:23,702
This theory remains a topic of debate to date.

377
00:15:23,702 --> 00:15:25,989
In 2010, the Mona Lisa Foundation

378
00:15:25,989 --> 00:15:29,024
started an investigation on the Isleworth Mona Lisa

379
00:15:29,024 --> 00:15:31,031
to find out the secret behind it.

380
00:15:31,031 --> 00:15:33,184
And they came up with another theory.

381
00:15:33,184 --> 00:15:36,767
They said that the face and hands of this new Mona Lisa

382
00:15:36,767 --> 00:15:38,056
were indeed painted by da Vinci.

383
00:15:38,056 --> 00:15:41,225
But the background was painted by an inferior artist.

384
00:15:41,225 --> 00:15:44,837
Perhaps, a person working in Leonardo's workshop

385
00:15:44,837 --> 00:15:47,630
had finished this painting.

386
00:15:47,630 --> 00:15:50,698
Both these theories remain mere theories

387
00:15:50,698 --> 00:15:54,036
because no solid evidence has been found on either side.

388
00:15:54,036 --> 00:15:56,025
Coming back to the theft of the Mona Lisa,

389
00:15:56,025 --> 00:15:59,214
it was found that the mastermind of this theft, Vincenzo Peruggia,

390
00:15:59,214 --> 00:16:01,531
was an employee in the Louvre Museum.

391
00:16:01,531 --> 00:16:03,650
One day, he hid in some corner in the museum

392
00:16:03,650 --> 00:16:05,592
and spent the night there

393
00:16:05,592 --> 00:16:09,207
after which, the next morning, he walked out with the painting.

394
00:16:09,207 --> 00:16:12,149
He believed that since Leonardo da Vinci was an Italian,

395
00:16:12,149 --> 00:16:15,026
this painting should be in an Italian museum.

396
00:16:15,026 --> 00:16:16,547
When the news of the theft spread,

397
00:16:16,547 --> 00:16:18,622
it made headlines all over the world.

398
00:16:18,622 --> 00:16:21,253
Scores of detectives were put to work

399
00:16:21,253 --> 00:16:23,848
to look for the thief.

400
00:16:23,848 --> 00:16:25,743
But no one could find him.

401
00:16:25,743 --> 00:16:30,269
For two years, Peruggia hid this painting at his home.

402
00:16:30,269 --> 00:16:32,646
He wondered what he could do with it.

403
00:16:32,646 --> 00:16:34,457
The whole world was looking for it.

404
00:16:34,457 --> 00:16:36,401
Finally, he became impatient

405
00:16:36,401 --> 00:16:38,084
and tried to sell the painting.

406
00:16:38,574 --> 00:16:43,068
He tried to sell this painting to an art dealer in Florence

407
00:16:43,068 --> 00:16:44,592
To Giovanni Poggi.

408
00:16:44,592 --> 00:16:46,158
Giovanni became suspicious

409
00:16:46,158 --> 00:16:49,506
and saw the stamp on the painting to confirm that

410
00:16:49,506 --> 00:16:51,794
it was the stolen painting.

411
00:16:51,794 --> 00:16:54,571
He was being sold the most wanted item in the world.

412
00:16:54,571 --> 00:16:56,760
Because of this, Vincenzo was caught

413
00:16:56,760 --> 00:16:58,759
and was sentenced to 6 months' imprisonment.

414
00:16:59,249 --> 00:17:02,729
The painting was sent back to the Louvre Museum

415
00:17:02,729 --> 00:17:05,690
and was hung up on 4th January, 1914.

416
00:17:05,690 --> 00:17:08,036
Today, this painting is displayed there,

417
00:17:08,036 --> 00:17:09,623
behind bulletproof glass,

418
00:17:09,623 --> 00:17:11,978
in strict climate-controlled conditions

419
00:17:11,978 --> 00:17:16,420
where humidity is maintained at 50% +/- 10%,

420
00:17:16,420 --> 00:17:20,593
temperature is strictly maintained at 18°C to 21°C.

421
00:17:20,593 --> 00:17:23,944
Perhaps the most interesting part in this story is that

422
00:17:23,944 --> 00:17:25,690
only after this theft

423
00:17:25,690 --> 00:17:28,086
did Mona Lisa's popularity start increasing.

424
00:17:28,086 --> 00:17:31,695
And it became the world's #1 famous painting.

425
00:17:31,695 --> 00:17:32,619
That's right.

426
00:17:32,619 --> 00:17:35,723
Before the theft, the Mona Lisa was not very famous.

427
00:17:35,723 --> 00:17:37,396
People who were interested in art,

428
00:17:37,396 --> 00:17:39,534
knew about the Mona Lisa but

429
00:17:39,534 --> 00:17:42,425
the common folks did not know about the Mona Lisa.

430
00:17:42,425 --> 00:17:45,132
So, if you go to the Louvre Museum

431
00:17:45,132 --> 00:17:47,089
and see the painting of the Mona Lisa

432
00:17:47,089 --> 00:17:49,604
and you see a crowd of people around it,

433
00:17:49,604 --> 00:17:54,317
then you can blame Vincenzo for this popularity.

